\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=(1-k)G+kS
\]

\end_inset

 hence
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
S & =A/k-(1-k)G/k;\\
G & =A/(1-k)-kS/(1-k).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Var(B|A) & =E(B^{2}|A)-E(B|A)^{2}\\
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
E(B|A) & =\\
 & =E(kG-(1-k)S|A)\\
 & =k(E(G|A))-(1-k)E(S|A)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E(G|A=a)=\frac{\int g\gamma(g)\sigma(a/k-(1-k)g/k)dg}{\int\gamma(g)\sigma(a/k-(1-k)g/k)dg}
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E(S|A=a)=\frac{\int s\gamma(a/(1-k)-ks/(1-k))\sigma(s)ds}{\int\gamma(a/(1-k)-ks/(1-k))\sigma(s)ds}.
\]

\end_inset

assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma,\sigma$
\end_inset

 are independent pdfs of 
\begin_inset Formula $G,S$
\end_inset

.
 Also note that the expressions at the bottom are the same - they are both
 the marginal pdf of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

; there's just been a change of variable.
 In fact we could express both of them as integrals over 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means we have got the expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $E(B|A)^{2}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k^{2}E(G|A)^{2}+(1-k)^{2}E(S|A)^{2}-2k(1-k)E(G|A)E(S|A)
\]

\end_inset

and, although it is a complicated beast, it does not have any horrible condition
al expectations in it.
 We can also probably draw both of these and think of them in terms of quasi-con
cavity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

